However, there is another gap related effect significantly contributing to the free energy: capacitive interaction between the CF tip and its opposite electrode. That interaction can be thought of as due to a flat plate capacitor formed by the tip’s end face and the opposite electrode, which may have a much larger area (for example in micron range) that can be approximated as infinite compared to the tip area. However the field distribution is strongly dominated by the smallest of the two plates, as was confirmed in our numerical COMSOL modeling. Using the flat plate capacitor formula leads to the energy contribution,11\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${F}_{C}=-\,\frac{C{U}^{2}}{2}\approx -\,\frac{\varepsilon {r}^{2}{U}^{2}}{8{h}_{{\rm{gap}}}}$$\end{document}FC=−CU22≈−εr2U28hgapwhere C is the flat plate capacitor capacitance, U is the voltage between the electrodes. Note that assuming other geometrical shapes of the tip (with the infinite opposite electrode) lead to only slightly different results28,29, where, for example, r is replaced with the electrode size in Eq. (11) for the case of hyperboloid of revolution29.

