				\begin{document}$$w/kT\gg 1$$\end{document}w/kT≫1. With that in mind, one can approximate the required barrier suppression vs. gap width, δw(E) = const + kT ln H, which dependence may be too weak to resolve experimentally.(ii)
Unlike FIN, the runaway model per se does not predict any delay time between voltage pulse and switching. The observed delay was attributed in that model to the thermalization time30 or left without explicit interpretation35.
We note here that the thermalization attributed delay time must be controlled by the conductivity, which is activated over the characteristic time τ ∝ exp[−δw(E)/T] [cf. Eq. (18)]. That delay time is exponential in voltage as intended to fit the data. That leads to the prediction that the delay time is reciprocal of the voltage dependent conductivity, which is open for experimental verifications. Note that FIN predictions for τ(U) are quite different as specified in Eqs (6) and (14).(iii)
